******
[3] Nigeria (Katsina)
Date: Wed 11 Aug 2021
Source: Daily Post [edited]
<dailypost.ng/2021/08/11/children-worse-hit-by-cholera-in-katsina-with-67-of-reported-cases/>


Katsina State has been hit by cholera cases in addition to the COVID-19 pandemic. Recently, the diarrheal illness caused by infection of the intestine with the bacterium _Vibrio cholerae_ has recorded a new high, with children being the most affected.

The commissioner for health in the state, Engr Yakubu Nuhu Danja, while briefing newsmen of the development in his office on Tuesday [10 Aug 2021], said cholera, which was first noticed in Funtua LGA of the state in May 2021, has killed at least 75 out of the 1534 persons affected as of 8 Aug 2021 in 25 of the 34 LGAs in the state. He further noted that 67% of the 1534 infections constitute of children within 15 years of age while overall 53% of the reported cases were males.

"Funtua LGA had the highest number of cases with 384, followed by Sabuwa with 232, Kafur 215, Charanchi 135, Kankara 71 and Jibia with 69 cases. In terms of mortality, Funtua also leads with 18, followed by Charanchi, which has 14, Jibia 11, Kankara 5, while Rimi and Sabuwa are having 4 each," the commissioner stated.

Engr Danja identified some of the challenges militating against the cholera fight in the state, including the wide practice of open defecation in some areas and insecurity, which is hindering the medical team access to some communities in the state. He also noted that the influx of visitors to cases on admission was another challenge.

The health commissioner urged members of the public to make deliberate effort at practicing personal and environmental hygiene by ensuring regular washing of hands with soap and water, boiling of water before drinking, proper cooking and storage of food, thorough washing of vegetables and fruits before eating, and washing of hands after using the toilet as well as proper disposal of feces and refuse.

[byline: Dunamis Ogalah]

